## Running the Project

### Clone Repository

```
git clone <repository-url>
cd InventoryManagement
```

### Run with Docker

Set the JWT signing key outside source control before starting the container.
The application reads it from `Jwt__Key`. Keep `Jwt__Issuer`,
`Jwt__Audience`, and `Jwt__AccessTokenLifetimeMinutes` in configuration unless
you need to override them per environment.

Production startup requires these configuration environment variables:

```
ConnectionStrings__DefaultConnection
Database__ApplyMigrationsOnStartup
Jwt__Issuer
Jwt__Audience
Jwt__Key
Cors__AllowedOrigins__0
Cors__AllowedOrigins__1
ReverseProxy__KnownProxies__0 or ReverseProxy__KnownNetworks__0
Swagger__Enabled
RateLimiting__Global__PermitLimit
RateLimiting__Global__WindowSeconds
RateLimiting__Global__QueueLimit
RateLimiting__Login__PermitLimit
RateLimiting__Login__WindowSeconds
RateLimiting__Login__QueueLimit
RateLimiting__Register__PermitLimit
RateLimiting__Register__WindowSeconds
RateLimiting__Register__QueueLimit
RateLimiting__RefreshToken__PermitLimit
RateLimiting__RefreshToken__WindowSeconds
RateLimiting__RefreshToken__QueueLimit
Authentication__AllowPublicRegistration
Bootstrap__Admin__Enabled
Bootstrap__Admin__UserName
Bootstrap__Admin__Email
Bootstrap__Admin__Password
```

Set `Authentication__AllowPublicRegistration=false` in Production unless
you intentionally want unauthenticated users to create accounts.
Set `Database__ApplyMigrationsOnStartup=false` in Production. Automatic
migrations are disabled by default in Production; when pending migrations exist,
startup logs the pending migration names and leaves the database unchanged.
Set `Bootstrap__Admin__Enabled=true` only when creating the first production
administrator. Remove or disable it after startup succeeds.
Set frontend CORS origins with indexed environment variables such as
`Cors__AllowedOrigins__0`, `Cors__AllowedOrigins__1`, and so on. Production
origins must be explicit HTTPS origins without paths, queries, fragments, or
wildcards. Local HTTP origins belong only in Development or Testing
configuration. JWT bearer authentication uses the `Authorization` header, so
CORS credentials are not enabled.
For reverse-proxy deployments, configure trusted forwarded-header sources with
`ReverseProxy__KnownProxies__0`, `ReverseProxy__KnownNetworks__0`, and
additional indexed entries as needed. Do not configure wildcard proxy trust.
Production Swagger is disabled by default; set `Swagger__Enabled=true` only
when you intentionally want to expose Swagger in that environment.
Rate limits use fixed windows and can be overridden with the
`RateLimiting__...` environment variables listed above. Set only numeric
limits and window durations; do not use secrets in rate-limit configuration.
Production logging is configured separately in
`InventoryManagement.API/appsettings.Production.json`. Logs keep traceId
correlation, avoid request and response bodies, drop events that carry common
secret-bearing property names, and retain 30 daily rolling files by default.

Run database migrations as a controlled pre-deployment step:

```
dotnet ef database update --project InventoryManagement.Infrastructure --startup-project InventoryManagement.API
```

Back up the SQLite database with SQLite's backup mechanism before production
deployments or maintenance. Do not copy the live database file while writes may
be active. See `docs/sqlite-backup-restore.md` for the verified local and Docker
database paths, timestamped backup commands, integrity checks, retention
guidance, and restore procedure.

```
docker compose up --build
```

For Production, use the production compose file instead of the local
Development compose file:

```
docker compose -f docker-compose.production.yml up -d --build
```

The production compose file runs the API and frontend as separate containers.
The API container keeps `ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Production`, stores the
database and logs in persistent Docker volumes, runs as the non-root .NET
runtime user, and checks `/health/ready`. The frontend container builds the
React/Vite app and serves static files with nginx. The frontend is not merged
into the backend container.

Create a private `.env` beside `docker-compose.production.yml` before running
production compose:

```
cp production.env.example .env
```

Set `VITE_API_BASE_URL` to the public URL that browsers should use for the API.
Set `Cors__AllowedOrigins__0` to the public frontend origin. Do not commit real
secrets; the checked-in `production.env.example` contains placeholders only.

For multiple clients, use the same codebase with separate deployments:

* one private `.env` per client
* one separate database volume or database file per client
* the same API and frontend images built from this repository

If bind mounts are used instead of named volumes, make sure the mounted
database and log directories are writable by the container user.

Production TLS is expected to terminate at a reverse proxy. Configure the
proxy to send `X-Forwarded-For` and `X-Forwarded-Proto`, and set
`ReverseProxy__KnownProxies__0` or `ReverseProxy__KnownNetworks__0` to trust
only that proxy or network. The app listens on HTTP port `8080` inside the
container and relies on forwarded headers for correct HTTPS behavior.

Swagger UI:

```
http://localhost:8080/swagger
```

Health checks:

```
http://localhost:8080/health/live
http://localhost:8080/health/ready
```

Use `/health/live` for process liveness and `/health/ready` for readiness
checks that require database connectivity. Health responses are intentionally
minimal and do not include connection strings or exception details.

The application automatically:

* Starts the API
* Persists database and log files using Docker volumes
* Applies pending EF Core migrations automatically only when configured, such as in Development

